The inhabitants of Messana were called Mamertini, as being the descendants of those mercenaries of Agathocles, who after his death (289 B.c.), instead of quitting Sicily, seized upon Messana, massacred all the male inhabitants, and established themselves there, calling themselves Mamertini, i. e. children of Mamers, which was an old Oscau name of Mars, under which title they claimed the right to make war without provocation. Arnold calls them ⁶ the Mamertine buccaneers‚’ and the parallel is a good one; the buccaneers called themselves, much in the same way, ‘ friends of the sea and enemies of all that sailed on it.’
